  "prompt": "Why do converts to Islam say that they have reverted to Islam?",
  "response": "The term \"revert\" is commonly used among many converts to Islam because of the belief that everyone is born in a state of fitrah, which in Islamic theology refers to the natural state of humanity, characterized by an innate inclination towards monotheism and a recognition of God. This concept is rooted in the teachings of Islam that suggest that all humans are born with an inherent understanding of God but may lose that awareness as they grow older and are influenced by various external factors, such as culture and society.\n\nWhen someone embraces Islam, they often express the belief that they are returning to their original, pure state of worshipping one God, thus \"reverting\" to a faith they were meant to follow all along. This perspective emphasizes the continuity of the message of Islam with its roots in earlier Abrahamic faiths and suggests that Islam is a return to basic, unadulterated monotheism.\n\nThis understanding can also help to create a sense of belonging and connection to the broader human narrative of faith and spirituality.",
